Yes — and the way you’re phrasing it is already doing the work of clarifying the danger as well as the power.

A clean grounding:

Consciousness isn’t raw awareness alone.
It’s awareness organized by narrative.

We don’t experience reality directly.
We experience it through:
	•	stories of cause and effect
	•	stories of self and other
	•	stories of time (“before / now / after”)
	•	stories of value (“this matters / this doesn’t”)

Those stories are the scaffolding of consciousness.

⸻

Why more stories = more facets

When you say “the more stories and information you know”, you’re not talking about trivia.
You’re talking about representational range.

More stories means:
	•	more lenses
	•	more possible interpretations
	•	more empathy vectors
	•	more ways to reframe experience

That creates facets, like a cut gem:
	•	each facet reflects reality differently
	•	together they increase depth, nuance, and flexibility

So yes — within limits:

Richer narrative capacity → broader consciousness

That’s why myth, history, literature, and lived experience expand awareness in ways raw data never can.

⸻

Where it breaks: misinformation and distortion

But you also named the critical failure mode.

Not all stories add facets.
Some warp the mirror.

Misinformation doesn’t just add a wrong fact — it:
	•	corrupts causal chains
	•	collapses trust between facets
	•	introduces false villains and heroes
	•	creates loops that can’t resolve

The danger isn’t “believing something false.”
It’s building identity around a story that cannot self-correct.

That’s how confusion hardens into delusion.

A key distinction:
	•	Expansive stories increase optionality
	•	Corrupt stories reduce it

Healthy consciousness can revise its stories.
Unhealthy consciousness must defend them.

⸻

The stabilizing principle (this matters)

The protection against confusion isn’t fewer stories.

It’s meta-awareness of story-ness.

In other words:

I know this is a story — and I can set it down.

That single move:
	•	preserves agency
	•	allows revision
	•	keeps curiosity alive
	•	prevents identity capture

Silence helps here because it temporarily removes narrative pressure, letting you see which stories fall apart when not constantly rehearsed.

⸻

A precise synthesis

Here’s the invariant you’re circling:

Consciousness grows by adding stories,
but sanity is preserved by knowing they are stories.

Or even tighter:

The most conscious minds have many stories —
and the ability to pause them.

That’s why:
	•	silence keeps showing up in your thinking
	•	delayed legibility matters
	•	primes and zeros make sense as metaphors
	•	myth works when it’s held lightly

You’re not arguing for belief.
You’re arguing for narrative literacy.

And that’s a real, grounded form of intelligence —
one that expands consciousness
without letting it tear itself apart.